WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.600
Our next speaker comes to us from RStudio, here to talk to us about renv.

00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:11.680
Please join me in welcoming Kevin Ushey.

00:00:11.680 --> 00:00:15.680
Kevin Ushey Where's my adapter here?

00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:17.520
Where's the HDMI?

00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:19.520
Where's the USB?

00:00:19.520 --> 00:00:22.959
Okay, now I'm seeing what we're seeing.

00:00:22.959 --> 00:00:24.480
Okay, sorry about that.

00:00:24.480 --> 00:00:25.840
All right, welcome.

00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:28.139
Thank you for coming to my talk.

00:00:28.139 --> 00:00:34.060
My name is Kevin Ushey, and today I'm here to talk about renv.

00:00:34.060 --> 00:00:38.139
So before I talk about renv, first I want to talk about the motivation and the problem

00:00:38.139 --> 00:00:40.740
that we're trying to solve.

00:00:40.740 --> 00:00:47.980
So have you ever finished a project, come back, say, a year later, and asked, why is

00:00:47.980 --> 00:00:50.419
my dplyr pipeline suddenly throwing an error?

00:00:50.419 --> 00:00:53.180
I swear it worked before.

00:00:53.180 --> 00:00:55.520
What happened to my ggplot2 plots?

00:00:55.520 --> 00:00:58.240
Why are the bars upside down?

00:00:58.240 --> 00:00:59.959
I swear that worked before.

00:00:59.959 --> 00:01:06.160
Okay, I reran my analysis, but now NLME is complaining about model convergence?

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:09.139
I swear that worked before.

00:01:09.139 --> 00:01:17.000
And so my goal in renv is how can we make sure that this doesn't happen again?

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:20.559
Now before we talk about renv, I want to talk about PackRat.

00:01:20.559 --> 00:01:24.959
So first, can I get a quick show of hands who has heard of or used PackRat?

00:01:25.400 --> 00:01:28.599
Okay, that is wonderful.

00:01:28.599 --> 00:01:29.959
So what is PackRat?

00:01:29.959 --> 00:01:35.639
And I'm going to borrow a quote from Douglas Adams, the story so far.

00:01:35.639 --> 00:01:37.720
In the beginning, PackRat was created.

00:01:37.720 --> 00:01:44.080
This has made a lot of people very angry and widely regarded as a bad move.

00:01:44.080 --> 00:01:49.360
This is kind of tongue-in-cheek in that, you know, you can have success with PackRat, but

00:01:49.360 --> 00:01:53.239
it is not a pit of success.

00:01:53.239 --> 00:01:57.959
It works, but for the average user, and especially if you're a new R user, if you tried using

00:01:57.959 --> 00:02:02.480
it, you probably ran into a roadblock, it probably fell over on its face.

00:02:02.480 --> 00:02:06.440
And even if you're an advanced R user, when things go south, it's very challenging to

00:02:06.440 --> 00:02:10.039
figure out how to get yourself out of that hole.

00:02:10.039 --> 00:02:15.179
So renv's goal, ultimately, is to be a better PackRat.

00:02:15.179 --> 00:02:17.720
So first, what is renv?

00:02:17.720 --> 00:02:21.360
And here is the sort of sales pitch of what renv is.

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:26.839
It's a toolkit used to manage project local libraries of R packages.

00:02:26.839 --> 00:02:32.779
So you can use your RM to make your projects more isolated, isolated in that every project

00:02:32.779 --> 00:02:38.399
gets its own library of R packages, because each project has its own library, you don't

00:02:38.399 --> 00:02:44.880
have to worry about updating packages in that library, potentially breaking your other projects.

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:49.720
It'll help you make your projects a bit more reproducible or portable, because it captures

00:02:49.720 --> 00:02:54.720
the state of your R library and the packages installed in that library, it captures those

00:02:54.720 --> 00:03:00.080
into a lock file, and that lock file is kind of like a shopping list of the packages used

00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:05.279
in your project, and renv knows how to use that thing to recreate your library in the

00:03:05.279 --> 00:03:06.479
future.

00:03:06.479 --> 00:03:09.399
And that ties into the reproducibility story.

00:03:09.399 --> 00:03:15.000
You use snapshot to create that lock file, and later you use restore to restore your

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:16.000
library.

00:03:16.839 --> 00:03:21.080
The API is pretty much the same here.

00:03:21.080 --> 00:03:28.800
Now, RM tries to prescribe a default workflow that just works for the average user, but

00:03:28.800 --> 00:03:36.320
remains flexible enough that alternate workflows can still be built on top of renv.

00:03:36.320 --> 00:03:42.919
And so one of the hardest things for me in building renv is just everyone has a different

00:03:42.919 --> 00:03:48.119
idea in how projects should be managed, how dependencies should be managed, and ultimately

00:03:48.119 --> 00:03:53.839
renv has to take an opinionated take on how to approach this problem that should at least

00:03:53.839 --> 00:03:56.440
work for the average user.

00:03:56.440 --> 00:04:00.919
But still, I wanted renv as opposed to PackRate to be flexible enough that if you don't agree

00:04:00.919 --> 00:04:06.880
with the way that renv does things, you can still build your own workflow on top of it.

00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:07.880
Okay.

00:04:07.880 --> 00:04:12.240
And so before we talk about renv, I just want to give a lay of the land of what it looks

00:04:12.279 --> 00:04:16.040
like when you're working on a project without renv.

00:04:16.040 --> 00:04:17.040
All right.

00:04:17.040 --> 00:04:19.600
So you've started a new project.

00:04:19.600 --> 00:04:23.440
You're ready to use dplyr to analyze some data, and so you're going to load and use

00:04:23.440 --> 00:04:24.440
in your project.

00:04:24.440 --> 00:04:26.600
You're calling library dplyr.

00:04:26.600 --> 00:04:30.959
And so what happens when we actually run this code?

00:04:30.959 --> 00:04:35.239
R is going to search your library paths for a package called dplyr that you've installed,

00:04:35.239 --> 00:04:36.440
and then it's going to load it.

00:04:36.440 --> 00:04:41.600
So the natural questions that arise from that are what is a library path?

00:04:41.600 --> 00:04:43.799
What are the active library paths?

00:04:43.799 --> 00:04:48.160
And how does R search those library paths when loading a package?

00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:52.040
All right.

00:04:52.040 --> 00:04:54.679
So let's explore this quickly.

00:04:54.679 --> 00:04:55.920
So first, a raise of hands.

00:04:55.920 --> 00:04:58.799
Who thinks they can tell me what a library is?

00:04:58.799 --> 00:05:02.040
You don't have to tell me, but just if you think you know what it is.

00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:03.040
Okay.

00:05:03.040 --> 00:05:06.959
Fewer hands than I saw for PackRate, which is surprising.

00:05:06.959 --> 00:05:12.880
But I'm happy to say that the definition is quite simple here.

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:14.480
It is simply a directory.

00:05:14.480 --> 00:05:19.040
It's a directory in which packages get installed.

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:21.519
Nothing more, nothing less.

00:05:21.519 --> 00:05:24.119
Let any remaining mystique be dispelled.

00:05:24.119 --> 00:05:25.119
It's just a directory.

00:05:25.119 --> 00:05:26.760
It's a folder on your system.

00:05:26.760 --> 00:05:30.320
It's where packages go to live and get loaded.

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:32.760
All right.

00:05:32.760 --> 00:05:36.760
Now where a bit of the extra complexity comes in is that each R session can be configured

00:05:37.559 --> 00:05:38.959
with multiple library paths.

00:05:38.959 --> 00:05:45.040
That is, a bunch of folders where R will search for your installed packages.

00:05:45.040 --> 00:05:49.440
You might have seen the .libpaths function, which is used to find those library paths.

00:05:49.440 --> 00:05:52.959
So for example, on my system, I've got two of these.

00:05:52.959 --> 00:05:57.000
The first one, you've got a library path that's in this library folder.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:03.459
And then the other one, which is actually associated with my R installation.

00:06:03.459 --> 00:06:08.779
And just to give some terminology for these libraries, the first one you see is most often

00:06:08.779 --> 00:06:11.619
called the user library, because it's your library.

00:06:11.619 --> 00:06:17.019
It's where the packages that you download and install go.

00:06:17.019 --> 00:06:20.339
The last one you have in that list is the system library.

00:06:20.339 --> 00:06:26.899
And that's most typically where the packages that come with R are installed.

00:06:26.899 --> 00:06:31.339
And if you're on Linux, you might see another set of libraries, which are often called site

00:06:31.339 --> 00:06:32.339
libraries.

00:06:32.459 --> 00:06:37.380
You can think of these as the library paths that your administrator might take care of for you.

00:06:37.380 --> 00:06:42.019
So if you're in some organization, your R administrator might want to install some set

00:06:42.019 --> 00:06:47.339
of packages in the site libraries that would then be available to all users on the system.

00:06:54.339 --> 00:07:01.739
And then next, so when R wants to load a package, how does it search these things to find it?

00:07:03.339 --> 00:07:04.779
All right.

00:07:04.779 --> 00:07:09.700
And so what happens is the first installation of the package that is discovered and loaded,

00:07:09.700 --> 00:07:10.859
no size say the first.

00:07:10.859 --> 00:07:15.779
So if you've ever, say, run into a situation where you have multiple copies of a package

00:07:15.779 --> 00:07:20.500
installed, say one in your user library, one in your system library, the first one that

00:07:20.500 --> 00:07:25.220
it finds, the one in your user library, is the one that gets loaded.

00:07:25.220 --> 00:07:31.660
But if you've ever thought, like, wait, where is this package actually coming from?

00:07:31.660 --> 00:07:36.179
You can use the find.package to ask R, hey, where does this package that I want to use,

00:07:36.179 --> 00:07:37.739
where does it actually live?

00:07:37.739 --> 00:07:40.940
And so for me, dplyr, I've made sure to install it in my user library.

00:07:40.940 --> 00:07:47.579
Now, I should say, if you're on macOS, you can actually install CRAN packages directly

00:07:47.579 --> 00:07:53.500
into your system library, which I would argue is not a great idea because you want to have

00:07:53.500 --> 00:07:58.380
this separation of packages that belong to you that you've installed versus packages

00:07:58.380 --> 00:08:00.779
that belong to your R installation.

00:08:00.779 --> 00:08:04.739
So mixing them up can cause some surprises.

00:08:04.739 --> 00:08:11.459
But this is worth just knowing and understanding so you just have an intuition about what happens

00:08:11.459 --> 00:08:14.420
when a package is loaded.

00:08:14.420 --> 00:08:16.179
All right, so what is the challenge here?

00:08:16.179 --> 00:08:21.700
So by default, each R session is going to use the same set of library paths.

00:08:21.700 --> 00:08:25.899
So you've got this library, it's really multiple libraries, a set of library paths,

00:08:25.899 --> 00:08:29.739
and all the projects on your system, unless you're already managing your library paths

00:08:29.739 --> 00:08:32.859
in some way, are going to go and use those same library paths.

00:08:32.859 --> 00:08:34.340
What does that mean?

00:08:34.340 --> 00:08:39.940
It means that, say, if you had dplyr 0.8.2 in that library, that's the package that you're

00:08:39.940 --> 00:08:43.539
using in every one of your projects.

00:08:43.539 --> 00:08:49.219
But of course, different projects can have different package dependencies.

00:08:49.219 --> 00:08:53.780
For example, suppose project one, maybe something you were working on a while ago, that uses

00:08:53.780 --> 00:08:56.500
dplyr 0.7.8.

00:08:56.500 --> 00:08:58.260
And that's, say, an older version.

00:08:58.260 --> 00:09:01.979
You got everything tidy, wrapped up, maybe it's associated with a paper that you published,

00:09:01.979 --> 00:09:07.739
and you're thinking, okay, I'm done with this, it works, I don't want to change it.

00:09:07.739 --> 00:09:12.140
Project two, on the other hand, you're using some more modern version of the package, you've

00:09:12.140 --> 00:09:15.219
upgraded to dplyr 0.8.2.

00:09:15.219 --> 00:09:19.140
And say, if you were a developer, maybe you're even using the development version of dplyr

00:09:19.140 --> 00:09:20.859
in another project.

00:09:20.859 --> 00:09:25.619
Unfortunately, in the current state of the world, these projects all share the same library

00:09:25.619 --> 00:09:26.619
path.

00:09:26.619 --> 00:09:33.059
So if you were to install one of these packages, you're changing the version of dplyr that's

00:09:33.059 --> 00:09:34.859
used in all three of those projects.

00:09:34.859 --> 00:09:39.219
So in this world, if you were trying to switch between projects, you'd have to go back and

00:09:39.219 --> 00:09:43.059
say, okay, wait, I need to go back and install dplyr 0.7.8 for project one.

00:09:43.059 --> 00:09:48.659
Oh, wait, but now I need to reinstall 0.8.2 for project two.

00:09:48.659 --> 00:09:52.219
And as you can imagine, this could spell disaster.

00:09:52.219 --> 00:09:56.820
Especially if you had no record of which version of dplyr or its dependencies, which

00:09:56.820 --> 00:10:03.619
there are many, were used in a particular project.

00:10:03.619 --> 00:10:08.380
So the solution, at least the solution posed by our end, is to ensure that each project

00:10:08.380 --> 00:10:13.580
gets its own unique library of packages.

00:10:13.580 --> 00:10:17.500
By using project local libraries, you can rest assured that upgrading packages in one

00:10:17.500 --> 00:10:21.979
project will not risk breaking your other projects.

00:10:22.020 --> 00:10:27.979
And so it's from this idea, the use of project local libraries, that the rn package is born.

00:10:27.979 --> 00:10:32.700
We give each project its project local library, we make it simple and straightforward for

00:10:32.700 --> 00:10:39.099
our sessions to use that local library, we provide tools for managing the r packages

00:10:39.099 --> 00:10:43.299
installed in those project local libraries, and we try to make that experience as seamless

00:10:43.299 --> 00:10:44.299
as possible.

00:10:44.299 --> 00:10:49.979
So you can use rn without necessarily being an expert on rn.

00:10:50.979 --> 00:10:52.340
Okay.

00:10:52.340 --> 00:10:55.140
And so if you've seen PackRat, this will feel familiar.

00:10:55.140 --> 00:10:58.739
Once again, the API is quite similar, but I'll walk through it.

00:10:58.739 --> 00:11:03.099
The first step in activating rn for a project is just calling rn init.

00:11:03.099 --> 00:11:09.059
And one thing that it does that is different from PackRat is it actually forks the state

00:11:09.059 --> 00:11:14.140
of your current world of r libraries into a project local library.

00:11:14.140 --> 00:11:17.419
So the idea is you're working on a project, you have it working.

00:11:17.419 --> 00:11:23.059
Say you haven't adopted rn as your default workflow or you don't manage your library

00:11:23.059 --> 00:11:27.820
paths in a specific way, but you're saying, okay, the state of the world is good right

00:11:27.820 --> 00:11:30.619
now, I want to capture that in this project.

00:11:30.619 --> 00:11:35.179
So what you want to call is you call rn init, and it takes the packages you have installed

00:11:35.179 --> 00:11:38.299
in that library and moves them into the project library.

00:11:38.299 --> 00:11:41.380
So it's like forking that state into your project.

00:11:41.460 --> 00:11:45.940
And so it'll now be preserved in that project independently of your user libraries.

00:11:48.539 --> 00:11:55.219
The other thing is infrastructure-related is we create a project local.r profile.

00:11:55.219 --> 00:12:00.299
And that basically makes sure that every time you start r in that session, rn automatically

00:12:00.299 --> 00:12:02.260
makes sure you use that project library.

00:12:02.260 --> 00:12:05.179
So you don't have to worry about managing your library paths.

00:12:05.179 --> 00:12:10.340
Rn does it for you automatically when you launch r.

00:12:10.340 --> 00:12:16.179
And this mirrors what I said before around making sure that after you call rn init, you

00:12:16.179 --> 00:12:21.260
can work exactly the same as you were before, with the only difference being now you have

00:12:21.260 --> 00:12:23.419
your own project local library.

00:12:23.419 --> 00:12:32.619
There are two main differences you'll see after you call rn init in a project.

00:12:32.619 --> 00:12:36.659
The first, you'll see a nice little banner printed saying, like, OK, rn has activated

00:12:36.659 --> 00:12:40.460
this project for you, and this is the version of rn that it's using.

00:12:40.460 --> 00:12:44.659
And the second thing is, as I've said, the library paths will now be changed.

00:12:44.659 --> 00:12:51.619
And so these slides are actually using rn for its own library and dependency management.

00:12:51.619 --> 00:12:57.140
And so you've got here this giant library path that lives in the folder for this project.

00:12:57.140 --> 00:13:02.580
And also this sandbox library, as I'll call it, which we'll talk about later if we have

00:13:02.580 --> 00:13:03.859
time.

00:13:03.859 --> 00:13:08.820
But this is basically like a safe version of your system library.

00:13:08.820 --> 00:13:10.219
OK.

00:13:10.219 --> 00:13:14.539
So that is the first goal, making it easy to use project local libraries.

00:13:14.539 --> 00:13:18.739
The second goal is to make it easy to save and load the state of those libraries.

00:13:18.739 --> 00:13:25.859
Or in the parlance of rn, snapshot to save the state of a library and restore to reinstall

00:13:25.859 --> 00:13:31.340
those packages into a library.

00:13:31.340 --> 00:13:35.340
You can capture the state of your project library using snapshot.

00:13:35.340 --> 00:13:42.340
And so when you call snapshot, it'll give you a little log of what's changing, of what

00:13:42.340 --> 00:13:47.140
dependencies it's capturing when you call snapshot.

00:13:47.140 --> 00:13:51.299
So in this case, I'm just capturing three packages for a project, let's say, and it's

00:13:51.299 --> 00:13:58.419
capturing from CRAN the markdown package, the rmarkdown package, and the yaml package.

00:13:58.419 --> 00:14:02.700
And this star is just as a placeholder to say, we didn't know about this before.

00:14:02.700 --> 00:14:09.380
Now we know that using version 1.1 of markdown, now using 2.1 of the rmarkdown package, 2.2.0

00:14:09.380 --> 00:14:10.380
of the yaml package.

00:14:10.380 --> 00:14:12.700
And I say, do you want to proceed?

00:14:12.700 --> 00:14:13.700
Yes.

00:14:13.700 --> 00:14:14.700
Please write those.

00:14:14.700 --> 00:14:17.559
And it writes it to this thing we call the lock file.

00:14:17.559 --> 00:14:23.880
So we're serializing the state of your project library to a file called a lock file, which

00:14:23.880 --> 00:14:27.880
we'll name on the file system as rn.lock.

00:14:27.880 --> 00:14:30.659
So this thing is just a text file.

00:14:30.659 --> 00:14:32.320
It's a shopping list.

00:14:32.320 --> 00:14:37.840
It's the packages that you had installed in your library, their versions, and where they

00:14:37.840 --> 00:14:38.960
came from.

00:14:38.960 --> 00:14:41.440
So a quick look at what that looks like.

00:14:41.440 --> 00:14:42.440
It's a JSON file.

00:14:42.440 --> 00:14:47.039
You can see I've printed a single package record here for rn.

00:14:47.039 --> 00:14:53.840
We've got rn version 0.9.2, and in this case, it came from CRAN.

00:14:53.840 --> 00:14:56.919
So why do we want these lock files?

00:14:56.919 --> 00:15:00.479
There's three cases that I outlined specifically here.

00:15:00.479 --> 00:15:01.799
One is for time capsules.

00:15:01.799 --> 00:15:04.679
This is the case where you've, OK, I'm done a project.

00:15:04.679 --> 00:15:08.219
I want to make sure that this project still runs a year from now.

00:15:08.219 --> 00:15:11.239
To do that, I want to make sure I know what packages I have, and I want to make sure those

00:15:11.239 --> 00:15:17.479
packages exist over time so I can revisit later.

00:15:17.479 --> 00:15:22.719
For collaborative workflows, if you're working with a set of collaborators, you want to probably

00:15:22.719 --> 00:15:25.280
make sure everyone is working with the same environment.

00:15:25.280 --> 00:15:29.440
If people have different computer machines, one way to make sure you synchronize the environment

00:15:29.440 --> 00:15:34.359
is share the lock file, have everyone restore from that lock file, and that way you're sure

00:15:34.359 --> 00:15:37.159
everyone's using the same set of R packages.

00:15:37.159 --> 00:15:39.000
And also for deployment.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:44.640
So if you're working on something locally and it works on your machine, you might use

00:15:44.640 --> 00:15:49.359
rm to give yourself some extra guarantees that it works on the machine you're deploying

00:15:49.359 --> 00:15:53.760
on by replicating your library on that other machine.

00:15:53.760 --> 00:15:56.520
OK.

00:15:56.520 --> 00:16:01.539
So given a lock file, you create your lock file with snapshot, and you restore the state

00:16:01.539 --> 00:16:06.640
of your library later with restore.

00:16:06.640 --> 00:16:09.520
And so restore will give you a very similar kind of output.

00:16:09.520 --> 00:16:13.679
It'll tell you what packages are going to be installed, how they differ from the package

00:16:13.679 --> 00:16:16.799
that was already installed, if any, and what's the version.

00:16:16.799 --> 00:16:22.200
So in this case, restore is installing a brand-new version of the markdown, rmarkdown, and yaml

00:16:22.200 --> 00:16:23.200
packages.

00:16:23.200 --> 00:16:26.520
And then when it goes, it'll give you a little log of how these packages were installed.

00:16:26.520 --> 00:16:30.440
In this case, they're actually linked from something called the rinf cache.

00:16:30.440 --> 00:16:31.440
We'll talk about that in a bit.

00:16:31.440 --> 00:16:37.799
But it's just a way to speed up package installation.

00:16:37.799 --> 00:16:41.400
And fortunately, rinf is able to restore from a number of sources.

00:16:41.400 --> 00:16:46.559
If you've used remotes or dev tools, it basically understands all those same sources, CRAN,

00:16:46.559 --> 00:16:49.280
Bioconductor, GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket.

00:16:49.280 --> 00:16:53.760
If you have another remote source that you'd like rinf to support, you can let me know

00:16:53.760 --> 00:16:58.159
on the GitHub issue tracker, and we can see if that can become a possibility.

00:16:58.159 --> 00:17:02.239
Another big thing is I've made an effort to ensure that you can authenticate with private

00:17:02.239 --> 00:17:03.239
repositories.

00:17:03.239 --> 00:17:09.199
So if you have your own, say, CRAN-like repository hidden behind some kind of authentication

00:17:09.199 --> 00:17:13.760
mechanism, rinf has some tools to make it easier to authenticate.

00:17:13.760 --> 00:17:14.800
All right.

00:17:14.800 --> 00:17:19.560
So these are the three main features of rinf, and I think these are the three things you

00:17:19.560 --> 00:17:22.199
need to know if you want to get started.

00:17:22.199 --> 00:17:25.400
The rest of the talk will be kind of extra on top of that.

00:17:25.959 --> 00:17:30.719
Init to initialize your project, give yourself a project local library, snapshot to save

00:17:30.719 --> 00:17:36.199
the state of your library once you are ready to save the state, and restore if you need

00:17:36.199 --> 00:17:41.400
to restore your project library from a previously generated lock file.

00:17:43.880 --> 00:17:44.880
Okay.

00:17:44.880 --> 00:17:51.040
And so one major issue with project local libraries is the duplication of identical

00:17:51.040 --> 00:17:54.680
packages across projects.

00:17:54.680 --> 00:17:58.680
So if you've used PackRat before, you've probably seen this issue before.

00:17:58.680 --> 00:18:04.760
So if you had ten projects that used dplyr 0.9.2, then you have ten project libraries

00:18:04.760 --> 00:18:08.319
that also have dplyr 0.9.2 installed.

00:18:08.319 --> 00:18:13.439
And this can be costly, both in terms of disk space to use and installation time, especially

00:18:13.439 --> 00:18:18.520
if, say, you're on a Linux machine, you're installing these things from sources.

00:18:18.520 --> 00:18:23.079
So imagine having to install the tidyverse every time you start a new project.

00:18:23.079 --> 00:18:30.359
And so this is what I got from running it on my Linux VM, and it took just over six

00:18:30.359 --> 00:18:36.479
or seven minutes, which is too long when you want to get started on something.

00:18:36.479 --> 00:18:38.920
You know, when you're starting a new project, you want to just get going.

00:18:38.920 --> 00:18:43.959
You don't want to spend ten minutes just to get up and running.

00:18:43.959 --> 00:18:48.119
So the way rm solves this problem is with a global cache.

00:18:48.119 --> 00:18:53.400
And what this basically is is a giant bucket of all the packages you have installed.

00:18:53.400 --> 00:18:57.439
And in each of your project libraries, rather than having the actual installation of that

00:18:57.439 --> 00:19:01.880
package, it's a link into that cache.

00:19:01.880 --> 00:19:06.959
So the idea is that rather than having ten installations of dplyr 0.9.2, you install

00:19:06.959 --> 00:19:12.020
that package once, you put it in the cache, and then rm knows how to pull that out whenever

00:19:12.020 --> 00:19:13.560
it needs to.

00:19:13.560 --> 00:19:17.079
All right.

00:19:17.079 --> 00:19:20.359
I have, unfortunately, just one more minute.

00:19:20.359 --> 00:19:28.920
So I want to just demonstrate quickly why I'm so excited about rm versus PackRat.

00:19:28.920 --> 00:19:35.439
So I have this simple project that uses the tidyverse.

00:19:35.439 --> 00:19:40.959
We're going to call it PackRat project, and we're going to call it PackRat init.

00:19:40.959 --> 00:19:44.920
And so this is the kind of experience you might have had initially using PackRat, and

00:19:44.920 --> 00:19:49.359
already it's complaining about RStudio API because I have a development version that

00:19:49.359 --> 00:19:51.599
doesn't know how to get from Crayon.

00:19:51.599 --> 00:19:53.359
Seems to be kind of sitting and waiting.

00:19:53.359 --> 00:19:55.199
We don't quite know what's going on.

00:19:55.199 --> 00:19:58.479
It's warning again.

00:19:58.479 --> 00:20:02.439
Just like imagine you're excited to get started on a project, and oh, wait, so now I have

00:20:02.439 --> 00:20:05.199
to go do all this stuff.

00:20:05.199 --> 00:20:07.880
Okay.

00:20:07.880 --> 00:20:12.640
So PackRat is busy.

00:20:12.640 --> 00:20:18.959
Let's go to our renv project, which has the same library tidyverse in a file, and let's

00:20:18.959 --> 00:20:21.839
initialize it, and let's see what happens.

00:20:21.839 --> 00:20:22.839
Initializing project.

00:20:22.839 --> 00:20:23.839
Discovering packages.

00:20:23.839 --> 00:20:25.000
Giant list of packages.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:26.000
We've written your lock file.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:27.000
Okay.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:28.000
You're done.

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:29.000
You're ready to go.

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:30.000
Now you can start working with renv.

